RulesName: Convert particular adjectives in predicative constructions to verbs
Comment: Instructions:  To convert a construction such as 'John is tall' to 'John talls', click on the Add Word button.  Then click on the adjective in the input structure.  Select the adjective that you want to change, in this case it would be 'tall'.  Then, if this is the first time you're using this rule, click on the New Translation button, and then click on the verb in the output structure.  Select the target verb that you want inserted into the text.  The rule is now ready to be used so you may save it by clicking the OK button.  Later, when you want to change another adjective to a verb, add that adjective to the input structure as was described above.  Then, while the Add Word button is still depressed, click on the verb in the output structure.  You'll see a table and the last row will be empty.  Click on the first cell in the last row and select the adjective that you just added to the input structure.  Then click on the next cell in the last row and select the target verb that you want inserted into the text.  The rule will then be ready to be used.  In the table you may specify as many adjective and verb combinations as are relevant for your language.  Note: Since this rule deletes the adjective, if the adjective's Degree was anything other than Not Applicable, that feature will be lost.  Therefore you need to handle the various possible values of Degree in the subsequent structures.  Those structures will be executed before this first structure.-*-  In the output structure, make whatever changes are necessary to indicate that the adjective's Degree is 'too, overly'.-*-  In the output structure, make whatever changes are necessary to indicate that the adjective's Degree is Extremely Intensified.-*-  In the output structure, make whatever changes are necessary to indicate that the adjective's Degree is Intensified.-*-

RulesName: When main verb's Time is Discourse and subordinate clause's verb is Present, set subordinate tense to Discourse
Comment: Infected Eye 1:7  Alex knew that Melissa's eyes were sick.  The verb in the object complement has a Tense of Present.   For object complement clauses, we don't inlcude future tense values.  Esther 2:17 The king decided that Esther will become the new queen.  Note: Previously none of these tense correction rules applied to direct quotes, so the Direct Quote 1 and Direct Quote 2 features were set to Not Applicable.
